   <category name='view'>

      <section name='enter'>

         <para number='1' comment='1st entry message for window'>
         The observation window is currently showing a view of the planet Earth, which moves slowly - oh so slowly - from one side to the other. The sight of the blue-green-white globe that is the cradle of mankind never fails to affect even those who haven't set foot on the planet.
         </para>

         <para number='2' comment='2nd entry message'>
         Through the window you can see an expanse of stars filling the blackness with points of light, together making up the milky way - the Galaxy in which the Solar System resides.
         </para>

         <para number='3' comment='3rd entry message'>
         Through the window you can see a cluster of ships hanging in space a short distance from Magellan. You think you can make out which ship is yours! Shuttles moving between the ships and the station are just visible as tiny moving specks.
         </para>

         <para number='4' comment='4th entry message'>
         Through the observation window you can see a huge cargo scow which has just lifted off from the cargo docking bays on wheel two. It drifts away in the direction of Mars, getting smaller and smaller until it finally vanishes from sight.
         </para>

         <para number='5' comment='5th entry message'>
         Through the window you can see a maintenance bot. You realise that as it moves, it is wiping the glass with its soft, cloth-like appendages - cleaning the accumulation of space dust off it to preserve the view.
         </para>

      </section>

      <section name='loop'>

         <para number='1' comment='First view from window'>
         The edge of the planet Earth appears on one side of the huge window, then slowly - oh so slowly - moves into full view. The sight of the blue-green-white globe that is the cradle of mankind never fails to affect even those who haven't set foot on the planet.
         </para>

         <para number='2' comment='2nd view from window'>
         Earth slides gently out of view and through the window you can see an expanse of stars filling the blackness with points of light, together making up the milky way - the Galaxy in which the Solar System resides.
         </para>

         <para number='3' comment='3rd view from window'>
         The station turns, bringing into view a cluster of ships hanging in space a short distance from Magellan. You think you can make out which ship is yours! Shuttles moving between the ships and the station are just visible as tiny moving specks.
         </para>

         <para number='4' comment='4th view from window'>
         A huge cargo scow moves ponderously past the window, having just lifted off from the cargo docking bays on wheel two. It drifts away in the direction of Mars, getting smaller and smaller until it finally vanishes from sight.
         </para>

         <para number='5' comment='5th view from window'>
         The view of the stars is interrupted by a maintenance bot which buzzes across from one side of the window to the other. It vanishes from sight, then reappears, traversing a different part of the glass. You realise that as it moves, it is wiping the glass with its soft, cloth-like appendages - cleaning the accumulation of space dust off it to preserve the view.
         </para>

